Date:10/22/2011 4:10:12 AM
From:J Mako
re: DAR

I value DAR as 2 entities: DAR and Griffin. Its avg capex matches its avg D&A.
So, reported earning is a good proxy of its FCF.

Using 2008-2010 3 year avg,

DAR EBIT = 80m.
Griffin EBIT = 108m
EV = 1.87B
EV/EBIT = 10
(equivalent to about P/E 15)

Including Griffin, DAR has bought 10 companies since 2004. Most of them were
small. The previous big one was National By Products in 2006. So, it looks like
DAR has been growing by acquisition.

The most obvious risk is another outbreak of BSE. Another risk is fluctuation
of commodity prices. But half of DAR's input cost and all of the Griffin's
input cost are based on "formula pricing". DAR is passing the fluctuation of
the prices of its commodity products to its suppliers to some extent. That
means DAR isn't that cyclical as compared to other Ag companies.

If DAR can maintain its growth, 10x EV/EBIT multiple isn't expensive. Its ttm
EBIT is 220m which includes only 1/2 yr of Griffin's profit. That's already 17%
above my historical average. What's hard to find out is how big the portion is
seasonal fluctuation.
